UNITED STATES OF AMERICA FEDERAL ENERGY REGULATORY COMMISSION BBT MISSISSIPPI, LLC STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS APPLICABLE TO NGPA SECTION 311(a)(2) TRANSPORTATION SERVICE BBT Mississippi, LLC, an intrastate pipeline operating within the State of Mississippi, will engage in the firm and interruptible transportation of natural gas pursuant to Section 311(a)(2) of the Natural Gas Policy Act of 1978 and pursuant to applicable regulations of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission on the terms and conditions contained herein.

The following is a statement of Transporter's currently effective maximum and minimum charges for service hereunder on BBT Mississippi, LLC's Pipeline System:

Reservation Rates $8.6688 (Monthly) $0.0000 (Monthly)

Fuel Use Percentage: Actual gas used by BBT Mississippi, LLC as compressor fuel, heater fuel, flare, company use and lost and unaccounted-for gas ("FL&U") or the amount set forth in Shipper's service agreement, not to exceed 4.25%, to be calculated and charged to shipper on a monthly basis.
Governmental Fees and Taxes: As set forth in Section 3.B of this Statement of Operating Conditions.
SECTION 1 DEFINITIONS A. The term, "Authorized Overrun Service," means an Overrun that is nominated by Shipper and approved and scheduled by Transporter.
B. The term, "Business Day," shall mean any day during a year, except Saturday, Sunday or Transporter's holidays. C. The term, "Btu," shall mean British Thermal Unit and, where appropriate, the plural thereof, and the term, "MMBtu," shall mean one million (1,000,000) Btu. D. The term, "Central Receipt Point," shall mean a receipt point on Transporter's system where measurement custody transfers to Transporter from a Shipper that has multiple wellheads upstream. E. The term, "Creditworthiness" shall mean, in the reasonable opinion of Transporter, Shipper's ability to pay for Transportation Service when due over the term of the Transportation Service Agreement. F. A "Cubic Foot of Gas," shall mean for the purpose of measurement of the gas delivered hereunder is the amount of gas necessary to fill a cubic foot of space at a pressure of 14.73 pounds per square inch, and at a temperature of sixty degrees (60o) Fahrenheit. The average atmospheric pressure shall be assumed to be 14.73 pounds per square inch absolute. G. The term, "Day," shall mean a period of twenty-four (24) consecutive hours beginning and ending at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time. "Day" may, for the purpose of changing of field charts, be extended to a period covered by the chart. H. The term, "Delivery Point," shall mean a point at the outlet side of Transporter's facilities at a point of interconnection between the facilities of Transporter and the facilities of Shipper or its designee. I. The term, "Electronic Data Interchange" or "EDI," shall mean electronic communication that complies with the Electronic Delivery Mechanism Standards of the North American Energy Standards Board ("NAESB") and its successors. J. The term, "FERC," shall mean the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. K. The term, "Firm", shall mean transportation or sales service that has the highest priority of service offered by Transporter. L. The term, "Fuel," shall mean the quantity of gas for Transporter's use, line loss and other unaccounted for losses on Transporter's Pipeline System. M. The term, "Gas," shall mean natural gas as produced in its natural state that meets the quality standards contained in these general terms. N. The term, "Governmental Fees," shall mean any and all privilege, franchise fees, charges, user fees or rentals levied by the governmental entities in exchange for the grant of privileges relating to use or improvements thereon, and any fees related to greenhouse gas emissions. O. The term, "Intraday Nomination," shall mean a nomination submitted to Transporter after the deadlines prescribed in the Standard NAESB nomination cycles for day ahead flow for quantities of Gas, which will be scheduled for receipt and delivery on the Gas Day of flow. P. The term, "Internet Home Page," shall mean Transporters' internet home page: https://www.lighthouseserv.com/customer-resources. Q. The term, "Interruptible", shall mean that the transportation of gas for the account of Shipper is subject to Transporter having sufficient capacity on the Pipeline System, not dedicated to firm service at the proposed time of transportation, to transport such gas at the time the gas is tendered. R. The term, "Maximum Daily Quantity" or the abbreviation "MDQ" as used herein, shall mean the maximum quantity of gas that Transporter will transport for Shipper in any one day, as provided for in the Shipper's Transportation Service Agreement. S. The term, "MCF," shall mean one thousand (1,000) cubic feet of gas. T. The term, "Month," shall mean a period beginning on the first (1st) day of the calendar month and extending to the first (1st) day of the following calendar month.
U. The term, "NGPA," shall mean the Natural Gas Policy Act of 1978.
V. The term, "New Taxes," shall mean any tax (other than ad valorem, income or excess profit taxes), license, fee or charge hereafter levied, assessed or made by any governmental authority on the gas itself or on the act, right or privilege of producing, severing, gathering, processing, transporting, handling, selling or delivering gas which is measured by the quantity, value or sales price of the gas. W. The term, "Pipeline System," shall mean all pipelines, compressors, and related facilities owned and operated by Transporter. X. The term, "Receipt Point," shall mean a point at the inlet side of Transporter's facilities at a point of interconnection between the facilities of Transporter and the facilities of Shipper or its designee. Y. The term, "Shipper," shall mean any party that has executed a Transportation Service Agreement with Transporter for transportation service subject to this Statement. Z. The term, "Taxes", shall mean any existing or hereafter enacted ad valorem, property, occupation, severance, production, extraction, first use, conservation, Btu or energy, gathering, transport, utility, gross receipts, gas or oil revenue, gas or oil import, privilege, sales, use, consumption, excise, lease, transaction, greenhouse gas, and other taxes or New Taxes, governmental charges or fees, licenses, fees, permits and assessments, or increases herein, and any interest or penalties on such taxes, charges, licenses, fees, permits, New Taxes based on such taxes, charges, licenses, fees, permits, and New Taxes, and assessments, other than taxes based on net income or net worth and Governmental Fees. AA. The term, "Thermally Equivalent," shall mean an equal amount of heating value, expressed in Btu and measured under the specifications and conditions contained hereunder. BB. The term, "Transportation Service," shall mean Firm or Interruptible transportation service as well as Authorized Overrun Service provided by Transporter pursuant to Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA. CC. The term, "Transportation Service Agreement," shall mean any contract of Transporter providing transportation service to a Shipper. DD. The term, "Transporter," shall mean BBT Mississippi, LLC. SECTION 2 RATES A. The rate to be paid by Shipper for service provided hereunder shall be agreed to by Shipper and Transporter, provided, however, that such rate shall not exceed the maximum rate nor shall it fall below the minimum rate approved for the services. B. Transporter's maximum rate for Transportation Service pursuant to Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA shall be determined pursuant to Section 284.123(b)(2) of FERC regulations. Transporter reserves the right to file for a higher maximum rate at any time. SECTION 3 FUEL AND TAXES A. Fuel may be paid in kind at Shipper's Receipt Points or in dollars per MMBtu for Transportation Service, as set forth in Shipper's Transportation Service Agreement. B. In addition to the charges pursuant to Section 2 and the Statement of Rates, upon billing, Shipper shall be liable for and shall pay, cause to be paid, or reimburse Transporter if Transporter has paid, causes to be paid or becomes obligated to pay, any Taxes or Governmental Fees attributable to or associated with any or all of the following: (i) any Transportation Service or transaction governed by this Statement of Operating Conditions performed by Transporter or its designee, and (ii) any of the facilities if Transporter or its affiliate(s) used to provide any service or transaction governed by this Statement of Operating Conditions. For clarity, Shipper shall be responsible for such Taxes and Governmental Fees only to the extent such amounts are not already reflected in Transporter's currently effective rates. Where such Taxes or Government Fees are not reflected in Transporter's currently effective rates, Transporter will make a filing at FERC for approval of the charging of such Taxes or Government Fees within thirty (30) days of billing Shipper. Shipper further agrees to pay any and all filing fees that Transporter or its designee may be required to pay to any regulatory agency or governmental body with respect to this Agreement, of the Transportation Service performed hereunder. The provisions of this Section shall survive termination of this Agreement. SECTION 4 REQUESTS FOR TRANSPORTATION SERVICE A. Transporter will accept as valid only those requests which, in Transporter's judgment are sufficiently specific with respect to the following information, all of which must be provided as set forth below: 1. Gas quantities, for which Transportation Service is requested, stated in MMBtu per day. 2. Receipt Points: a. Points of entry into Transporter's Pipeline System. b. Name of entity delivering gas into Transporter's Pipeline System. 3. Delivery Points: a. Points of delivery out of Transporter's Pipeline System. b. Name of entities to which Transporter delivers gas on Transporter's Pipeline System. 4. Term of proposed service: a. Date service is requested to commence. b. Date service is requested to terminate.
5. Certification that the Shipper has a current contractual right to take possession of the gas to be delivered to Transporter for transportation, and will enter into those arrangements necessary to ensure all upstream and downstream transportation will be in place prior to the execution of a Transportation Service Agreement by Transporter. 6. The name, address, title and telephone number of the corporate officer of Shipper who will execute the Transportation Service Agreement. 7. For NGPA Section 311 Transportation Service, a statement indicating the "on behalf of" entity(ies) that Shipper warrants meets the provisions of Section 284 of the Commission's Regulations. 8. Type of service requested: Firm Transportation or Interruptible Transportation. 9. Rate Requested 10. Request for Service may be sent to: BBT Mississippi, LLC 1501 McKinney St. Suite 800 Houston, Texas 77010
P.O. Box 1227 Houston, TX 77251
Attention: Commercial Services; Legal Email: Legal@blackbearllc.com; Contracts@lighthouseserv.com; GMatthews@blackbearllc.com
Phone Number: (281) 955-4800 B. Unless waived by Transporter, requests for Transportation Service hereunder will be invalid and will not be considered if a Transportation Service Agreement is not entered into within forty-five (45) days of the date of receipt of the information specified in this section; provided, however, that in no event will Transporter be required to perform service hereunder prior to such time that Shipper satisfies such condition. Requests which cannot be provided due to insufficient capacity, or because of a failure to satisfy the terms of this Statement of Operating Conditions within forty-five (45) days of the date the request is made, shall not be of a continuing nature and shall be deemed a nullity for all present and future purposes. C. Shipper may request and Transporter may agree to add or delete Receipt Points or Delivery Points on its Transportation Services Agreement. Agreement shall not be unreasonably withheld. SECTION 5 TERM AND TERMINATION A. Service will be provided for an agreed upon term; provided, however, Transporter shall have the right to terminate or suspend Interruptible Transportation Service immediately upon notice of such termination or suspension given to a Shipper in the event (i) Transporter, on a non-discriminatory basis, shall also concurrently terminate or suspend, as the case may be, all of its NGPA Section 311(a)(2) Interruptible Transportation Services of the same type as that service which was terminated or suspended, or (ii) deliveries of gas for transportation under the Interruptible Transportation Service Agreement, once commenced, have ceased for any period of ninety (90) consecutive days or more and not resumed. SECTION 6 CREDITWORTHINESS A. Transporter shall not be required to perform or continue to perform services on behalf of any Shipper that (i) has applied for bankruptcy under any chapter of the Bankruptcy Code, (ii) has failed to make prompt and full payments to Transporter when due for Transportation Services rendered by Transporter, or (iii) fails, in Transporter's reasonable judgment, to demonstrate Creditworthiness. B. Shipper may receive service if (i) Shipper prepays, or (ii) upon fifteen (15) days' notice from Transporter, furnishes good and sufficient surety bond or other good and sufficient security, as determined by Transporter in its discretion, or a continuing nature. The amount prepaid or of the security shall be equal to the charges for the Transportation Service requested by or provided to Shipper for up to a three (3) month period. Such limit of three (3) months of charges for Transportation Service shall not apply in the situation where Transporter has agreed to construct or acquire facilities in order to provide the Transportation Service for Shipper. The amount of security required to support the construction or acquisition of facilities is at the reasonable discretion of Transporter or as negotiated with the Shipper. C. If, in the reasonable opinion of Transporter, Shipper's Creditworthiness becomes unsatisfactory, Transporter may require assurance of Shipper's ability to pay or require different terms of payment. Such assurance may, at the option of Transporter, include (i) the required posting of a Letter of Credit in form and from a financial institution acceptable to Transporter; (ii) cash prepayments; or (iii) other delivery of other security acceptable to the Transporter, in an amount consistent with Section 6.B. Upon receipt of such notice, Shipper shall have two (2) Business Days to provide the assurance demanded by the Transporter and the Transporter shall have the right to withhold payment, and/or suspend deliveries from the time that the Transporter requests such assurances until such assurances are provided. In the event such assurance is not provided within two (2) Business Days of receipt of notice, then a breach of the applicable Transportation Service Agreement(s) will be deemed to have occurred and the Transporter shall be entitled to (i) terminate one or more Transportation Services Agreements with Shipper, (ii) liquidate gas balances in Transporter's position for the purpose of paying all amounts that become owing for services under any Transportation Service Agreements governed by this Statement of Operating Conditions, and (iii) seek all other remedies available for breach of the applicable Transportation Service Agreement(s). SECTION 7 NEW FACILITIES A. Transporter shall not be required to provide any requested Transportation Services which would require construction or acquisition by Transporter of any new facilities or expansion of Transporter's existing facilities. Transporter, in its reasonable discretion, may agree to construct or acquire new facilities, or expand existing facilities, to provide service requested by any Shipper. In such event, Shipper agrees to reimburse Transporter for the total incremental cost of the new facilities or expansion of existing facilities, unless otherwise mutually agreed in writing. Transporter shall determine method of reimbursement, either lump sum or installment. B. To the extent Transporter agrees to construct or acquire any new facilities or expand existing facilities, any such facilities shall be contracted, maintained, owned, and operated by Transporter, except as may otherwise be mutually agreed in writing. The design and installation of all facilities shall be in accordance with the specifications determined by Transporter in its reasonable discretion. SECTION 8 NOMINATIONS A. Within five (5) Business Days prior to the beginning of the Month, Shipper or its representative shall submit via Transporter's Internet Homepage to Transporter Shipper's best estimate of its daily requirements for Transportation from each of the Receipt Points and to each of the Delivery Points for the following month. Such estimates shall be stated in MMBtus. B. Shipper shall nominate gas by notifying Transporter of the daily quantity of gas in MMBtus it has available at the Receipt Points and of the quantity of gas it desires to have delivered at the Delivery Points. The total volumes to be delivered for the account of Shipper by Transporter must equal the total receipt nominations plus Fuel if applicable and any other adjustments. C. All nominations shall include Shipper-defined begin dates and end dates. All nominations should have roll-over options. Specifically, Shippers should have the ability to nominate for several Days or a Month, provided the nomination begin and end dates are within the term of the Shipper's contract. D. All nominations shall include the following components: Delivery location, delivery rank, Downstream ID ("Dn ID"), quantity, receipt location, receipt rank, Upstream ID ("UP ID"), service requestor, transaction type, and such other information as Transporter may request from Shipper. E. All times listed in this Section 8 are Central Clock time. F. Nominations must be submitted in writing via the Internet Home Page and must include the information specified in A through D, above, of this Section 8. G. A Shipper may avail itself of the daily nomination cycles promulgated by NAESB and adopted, to the extent codified, by FERC in its regulations. H. All nominations will be confirmed by the upstream or downstream connected party through the Internet Homepage or EDI. At least one service provider (including a point operator) shall provide a confirmation for a quantity of gas with respect to a nomination at a location on each side of a physical location. I. With respect to the timely nomination or confirmation process at a Receipt Point or Delivery Point, in the absence of agreement to the contrary, the lesser of the confirmation quantities will be the confirmed quantity. If a Shipper does not respond to a request for confirmation or if the confirmation response is unsolicited, the lesser of the confirmation quantities or the previously scheduled quantity will be the new confirmed quantity. J. With respect to the processing of requests for increases during the Intraday Nomination or confirmation process, in the absence of agreement to the contrary, the lesser of the confirmation quantities will be the new confirmed quantity. If a Shipper does not respond to a request for confirmation or if the confirmation response is unsolicited, the previously scheduled quantity will be the new confirmed quantity. K. With respect to the processing of requests for decreases during the Intraday Nomination or confirmation process, in the absence of agreement to the contrary, the lesser of the confirmation quantities will be the new confirmed quantity, but in any event no less than the quantity remaining after elapsed prorated scheduled quantity ("EPSQ") has been apportioned. If a Shipper does not respond to a request for confirmation or if the confirmation response is unsolicited, the greater of the confirmation quantities or the EPSQ will be the new confirmed quantity. L. A Shipper may delegate to any third party (an "Agent") the responsibility for submitting nominations and receiving confirmations or performing other administrative duties under any service agreement, subject to the following conditions: 1. Any designation of a third party as an Agent, or any change in such designation, must be provided in writing to Transporter at least two (2) Business Days prior to the requested effective date of the designation. 2. The written designation shall specify any limits on the authority of the Agent, including any time limit for the designation. 3. Transporter will rely on communications from a Shipper's Agent for all nomination purposes except to the extent the designation is explicitly limited. Limitations must be clearly specified. Shipper will hold Transporter harmless and shall indemnify Transporter for any losses incurred by Transporter in the event of Transporter's good faith interpretation of a limitation proves inconsistent with the intent of the limitation. Transporter reserves the right to reject delegations for reasons of unclear or impracticable limitations placed thereon. Communications by Transporter to such Agent shall be deemed notice to Shipper except to the extent the Agent's authority is explicitly limited as follows: i. With respect to the receipt of notice, the provisions of this Statement of Operating Conditions. ii. With respect to an Agent for one or more Shippers, any third party may administer multiple service agreements; however, the Agent shall administer and account separately for each Service Agreement. iii. With respect to an agent's authority, each Agent must execute the agency agreement in the form posted on Transporter's Internet Website prior to being authorized to act for a Shipper. SECTION 9 SCHEDULING Capacity on Transporter's Pipeline System shall be scheduled each day in the following order and manner: A. Firm service shall receive first (1st) priority. Within this category, Transporter shall schedule nominated service on a pro rata basis based on Shipper nominations.
B. Interruptible Service and Authorized Overrun Services shall receive second priority. Within this category, Transporter shall schedule nominated service on an economic basis. As such, Transporter shall accord service paying a higher rate per MMBtu a higher priority than service paying a lower rate. If two (2) or more Shippers are paying the same rate per MMBtu, Transporter shall schedule nominated service on a pro rata basis. Transporter will provide an interruptible Shipper whose service is being subordinated by this provision the right to increase the rate paid by Shipper to (i) the highest current intrastate transportation rate; or (ii) the highest current Section 311(a)(2) transportation rate, in order to avoid such subordination. An interruptible Shipper shall offer to pay such higher rate by making such offer on its nomination. C. Imbalance correction quantities nominated under any Transportation Service Agreement shall receive third priority. Within this category, Transporter shall schedule nominated service on a pro rata basis. SECTION 10 PRE-DETERMINED ALLOCATIONS A. The operator of each meter shall provide to Transporter a Pre-Determined Allocation ("PDA"); provided, however, such PDA must be acceptable to and capable of being implemented by Transporter. The PDA shall be used to allocate gas quantities at each meter. B. For meters physically behind or attributable to a Central Receipt Point, the meter operators or their representative will provide the PDA at the Central Receipt Point meter. C. All PDA's shall be received in accordance with the nomination deadlines specified in Section 8. D. In the event a PDA is not received from the operator of a meter or its representative, the PDA will default to a pro rata allocation based on Shipper nominations. PDA's received after the referenced deadlines shall be accepted at Transporter's discretion. SECTION 11 BALANCING A. Transporter shall deliver to Shipper or its designee at the Delivery Point on a daily basis, quantities thermally equivalent to quantities received, less fuel, if applicable, unless otherwise mutually agreed to in writing. Transporter, upon notice to Shipper which shall be given at least twenty-four (24) hours in advance unless exigent circumstances dictate otherwise, may issue "Operational Flow Orders" to require adjustments to Shipper's daily scheduling of receipts and/or deliveries over a reasonable period of time in order to maintain a concurrent balance when the operational integrity and/or safe operation of Transporter's Pipeline System would otherwise be threatened or result in inefficient or unreliable service.
B. If Shipper is advised by any upstream or downstream Transporter or operator to reduce or suspend deliveries for transportation, Shipper shall immediately notify Transporter orally, and shall confirm such notification in writing, of such reduction or suspension, and adjust its nominations at Receipt Points and/or Delivery Points in order to maintain a balanced position. C. Shipper shall be responsible for and shall bear any penalties imposed, claims made, or judgments imposed (collectively called "Liability") by either (i) upstream and downstream Transporters for imbalances between Receipt and Delivery Points; or (ii) well operators or well interest owners for production imbalances among the interest owners in a well. Shipper shall indemnify and hold Transporter harmless from all such Liability, including court costs and reasonable attorney fees, unless such Liability is found to be the direct result of Transporter's negligence. D. Prior to initiating corrective action, Transporter will provide to Shipper information regarding any current or potential imbalance situation, and Shipper shall adjust nominations at Receipt Points and/or Delivery Points in order to maintain a balanced position. However, if conditions threaten the integrity or safe operation of Transporter's Pipeline System then corrective action may be immediately taken. If Shipper believes such information is inaccurate, it shall immediately provide Transporter the information it believes to be contrary to Transporters conclusion for verification prior to corrective action. SECTION 12 CURTAILMENT A. Transporter shall have the right to curtail or discontinue transportation services in whole or in part on all or a portion of its system at any time for reasons of force majeure or when in Transporter's reasonable judgment, capacity or operating conditions so require, or it is desirable or necessary to make modifications, repairs or operating changes to its system. B. Transporter shall provide Shipper such notice of the curtailment as is reasonable under the circumstances. In the event curtailment of Transportation Service is required, service quantities shall be curtailed in the reverse order of the priority in effect at the time of curtailment established during scheduling as set forth in Section 9. SECTION 13 FORCE MAJEURE A. In the event Transporter or Shipper is rendered unable, wholly or in part, by reason of force majeure to carry out its obligations under the Transportation Service Agreement (other than the obligation to make payment of amounts due hereunder), it is agreed that such party shall give notice and reasonably full particulars of such Force Majeure, in writing, by telephone, facsimile, or other electronic means to the other party within a reasonable time after the occurrence of the cause relied on, and the obligations of the party giving such notice, so far as they are affected by such Force Majeure, shall be suspended during the continuance of any inability so caused, but for no longer period, and such cause shall, so far as possible, be remedied with all reasonable dispatch. B. The term, "Force Majeure," as employed herein shall mean acts of God; strikes, lockouts, or other industrial disturbances; conditions arising from a change in governmental laws, orders, rules, or regulations; acts of public enemy; wars; blockades; insurrections; riots; epidemics; landslides; lightning; earthquakes; fires; storms; floods; washouts; arrests and restraints of governments and people; civil disturbances; explosions; breakage or accident to machinery or lines of pipe; the necessity for making repairs, tests, alterations, or performing maintenance to machinery, facilities, or lines of pipe, but not including planned or scheduled maintenance; freezing of wells, lines of pipe or processing facilities; and any other causes, whether of the kind herein enumerated or otherwise, not reasonably within the control of the party claiming relief hereunder, and which by the exercise of due diligence, such party is unable to prevent or overcome. Such terms shall likewise include, but not be limited to: (i) those instances where either Transporter or Shipper is required to obtain servitudes, rights-of-way, grants, permits or licenses to enable such party to fulfill its obligations under the Transportation Service Agreement; the inability of such party to acquire, or the delays on the part of such party in acquiring, at reasonable costs, and after the exercise of reasonable diligence, such servitudes, rights-of-way, grants, permits, or licenses; (ii) those instances where either Transporter or Shipper is required to furnish materials and supplies for the purpose of constructing or maintaining facilities or is required to secure permits or permissions from any governmental agency to enable such party to fulfill its obligations under the Transportation Service Agreement, the inability of such party to acquire, or the delays on the part of such party in acquiring, at reasonable costs, and after the exercise of reasonable diligence, such materials and supplies, permits and permissions; and (iii) in those instances in which Transporter utilizes facilities of another entity or entities to transport gas under the Transportation Service Agreement, the failure of such other entity or entities to transport such gas. Force Majeure shall not include failure of gas supply due to pricing considerations. C. It is understood and agreed that the settlement of strikes or lockouts shall be entirely within the discretion of the party having the difficulty, and that the above requirement that any Force Majeure shall be remedied with all reasonable dispatch shall not require the settlement of strikes or lockouts by acceding to the demands of the opposing party when such course is inadvisable in the discretion of the party having the difficulty. D. Notwithstanding the foregoing, it is specifically understood and agreed by Transporter and Shipper that Force Majeure shall, in no way, terminate the parties' obligations to resolve Imbalances in accordance with the terms provided for herein.
E. Reservation Rate Crediting. 1. Reservation Rate Credits for Force Majeure Curtailments. To the extent Transporter fails to schedule or deliver Firm Transportation properly nominated by Shipper in accordance with this Statement, on any day due to a Force Majeure event that excuses performance under this Section 13:
i. Shipper shall remain liable for all Reservation Rates, as set forth in the applicable Firm Transportation Agreement, and amounts due or that become due under Shipper's Firm Transportation Agreement during the first ten (10) Days of a Force Majeure event.
ii. Following such ten (10) Day period, Transporter shall provide Shipper Reservation Rate credits in accordance with this Section 13, Paragraph E, for the nominated Firm Transportation quantity that Transporter failed to schedule or deliver to the Delivery Points due to such Force Majeure event.
iii. Outages resulting from one-time, non-recurring government requirements, including special, one-time testing requirements after a pipeline failure, are Force Majeure events only requiring Reservation Rate crediting after such ten (10) Day period.
2. Reservation Rate Credits for Non-Force Majeure Curtailments. To the extent Transporter fails to deliver Firm Transportation properly nominated by Shipper in accordance with this Statement on any Day due to reasons other than a Force Majeure event, Transporter shall provide Shipper Reservation Rate credits in accordance with this Section 13(E), for the nominated Firm Transportation quantity that Transporter failed to schedule or deliver to the Delivery Points.
3. Quantities to which Reservation Rate Credits Apply. Reservation Rate credits shall apply to quantities nominated under Shipper's Firm Transportation Agreement from a Receipt Point to a Delivery Point up to the MDQ in the effected Transportation Agreement that Transporter has been unable to schedule or deliver due to a Force Majeure event. Notwithstanding the foregoing:
(i) When Transporter provides notice of a Force Majeure event, prior to Shipper's first opportunity to nominate service for the applicable Day, the maximum potential quantity to which Reservation Rate credits may apply is the average of the quantities, not exceeding the MDQ in the affected Transportation Agreement, that were scheduled and delivered to Shipper under the affected Firm Transportation Agreement for the affected pair of Receipt and Delivery Points over the seven (7) Days of service immediately preceding the Force Majeure event causing service curtailment.
(ii) Reservation Rate credits shall not be available to the extent Shipper utilizes secondary Receipt or Delivery Points for a portion of the nominated quantities that would otherwise be subject to crediting.
(iii) Reservation Rate credits shall not be available to the extent (A) Transporter is able to restore service during the affected Day or (B) Shipper fails to re-submit its nomination in a later cycle unless, after receiving notice of Transporter's curtailment, for the affected Day (X) Shipper either has nominated and has been scheduled service on another pipeline or (Y) has made alternative arrangements for delivery of such gas as a result of Transporter's curtailment of service, and (Z) Shipper has provided verification of such arrangements to Transporter.
4. Calculation of Reservation Rate Credits. Transporter shall calculate daily Reservation Rate credits as the product of the daily Reservation Rate per MMBtu applicable to Shipper's Firm Transportation Agreement (discounted Reservation Rates, if applicable) multiplied by the gas quantity subject to Reservation Rate crediting, calculated in accordance with Section 13(E)(3). Transporter shall reflect any Reservation Rate credit due to a Shipper on the Shipper's monthly invoice, which credit shall be applied first to offset any outstanding past due balance.
5. Curtailments Due to Shipper or Third-Party Action. Reservation Rate credits shall be reduced to the extent any subject curtailments are the result of Shipper's negligence, intentional wrongful acts of Shipper, or Shipper's failure to comply with the provisions of this Statement. A Shipper shall not be entitled to Reservation Rate credits when Transporter's failure to schedule or deliver Shipper's nominations is due solely to the conduct of others, including upstream and downstream transporters, not controllable by Transporter.
6. Other Exclusions from Reservation Rate Credits. Notwithstanding any other provision in this Statement, in no event shall Shipper be entitled to Reservation Rate credits for failure to deliver any quantity of gas in the following situations:
(i) Due to the installation of new facilities that are designed, in whole or in part, to provide service to Shipper;
(ii) Due to scheduled work on Transporter's facilities if Transporter and Shipper have mutually coordinated the timing of the scheduled work and the work is performed in accordance with that schedule;
(iii) That occurs at a time when Shipper was unable to take the scheduled quantities for any reason including, a Shipper outage, whether planned or unplanned;
(iv) That was allocated or scheduled during any subsequent nomination cycle to or from a secondary location after the timely cycle restrictions;
(v) If Shipper subsequently schedules and accepts at an alternative point of delivery the quantity of gas that Transporter was unable to initially deliver; or
(vi) Due to the violation by Shipper of an Operational Flow Order and such violation causes a Force Majeure event resulting in the outage.
7. Limitation of Liability. Transporter's liability for failure to schedule or deliver Shipper's nominated Gas quantities, as described in this Section 13, shall be limited to Reservation Rate credits in accordance with this Section 13. SECTION 14 CASH-OUT PROVISIONS A. Gas volumes hereunder shall be delivered to Transporter and redelivered to Shipper as nearly as practicable at uniform hourly and daily rates of flow. After the transportation month, Transporter shall resolve all imbalances with Shipper through a cash payment or cash receipt, as applicable. To the extent that Shipper's delivered volumes are greater than Shipper's received volumes ("Due Pipeline"), Transporter will invoice Shipper for the imbalance based on the Net Monthly Imbalance times an Imbalance Multiplier and multiplied by the Posted Price. To the extent that Shipper's delivered volumes are less than Shipper's received volumes ("Due Shipper"), Transporter will make a payment to Shipper for the imbalance based on the Net Monthly Imbalance times an Imbalance Multiplier and multiplied by the Posted Price.
B. The "Posted Price" shall be equal to the production month's arithmetic average Index price per MMBtu of the weekly reference "Spot Price" figures established for the month (Bid Week Reference "Spot Price" for the first week of every month. For all other weeks the weekly Reference "Spot Price" is used). Unless otherwise noted, the data source will be the Index price, set forth for "Spot Gas Prices" as published each week in "Natural Gas Intelligence Gas Price Index" for Transco Zone 4. Should the information necessary to calculate the Posted Price cease to be available, Transporter and Shipper shall mutually agree upon substitute publication(s) providing equivalent data. C. The Shipper's imbalance percentage shall be calculated by dividing the Net Monthly Imbalance by the Shipper's allocated Delivery Point volumes. The Net Monthly Imbalance is equal to the absolute value of the allocated Receipt Point volume less fuel, less lost and unaccounted for and less the allocated Delivery Point volume. The Imbalance Multiplier shall be determined using the table below for either the excess (due Shipper - received is greater than delivered) or shortage (due Pipeline - received is less than delivered). If the imbalance is less than one thousand (1,000) MMBtu, the Imbalance Multiplier shall be 100%. Imbalance Tolerance (%) Imbalance Multiplier (%) (Due Transporter) Imbalance Multiplier (%) (Due Shipper) Less than or equal to 5 100 100 Greater than 5, less or equal to 10 110 90 Greater than 10, less than or equal to 20 120 80 Greater than 20 150 50
D. Transporter may waive or discount cash-out payments required under this Section 14.
SECTION 15 MINIMUM QUANTITY Transporter shall have the right to refuse to provide service or to suspend service at any Receipt Points or Delivery Points, if, in Transporter's opinion, deliveries of Gas at any such Receipt Points or Delivery Points during any Month are expected to average less than one thousand (1,000) MMBtu per Day during any such Month. Transporter shall have the right to terminate the Agreement or any transaction as to service at any Receipt Points or Delivery Points on thirty (30) days' written notice to Shipper if deliveries of Gas at any Receipt Points or Delivery Points during any Month average less than one thousand (1,000) MMBtu per Day during such Month. Transporter shall be deemed released from all obligations and liabilities concerning the continued acceptance or delivery of gas at such Receipt Points or Delivery Points under the Transportation Service Agreement upon the effective date of the suspension or termination of such service; provided, however, that Transporter's right to terminate shall not apply if (i) Shipper notifies Transporter in advance that Shipper does not wish to obtain service during the Month of deficient deliveries or (ii) the deficiency is due to an interruption of service by Transporter. SECTION 16 QUALITY SPECIFICATIONS A. All gas received or delivered hereunder, shall conform to the following specifications: 1. Water: The gas shall not have a water content in excess of 7 pounds of water per million (1,000,000) cubic feet of gas measured at a pressure base of 14.73pounds per square inch absolute and at a temperature of sixty degrees (60o) Fahrenheit. 2. Hydrogen Sulfide: The gas shall not contain more than 1/4 grain(s) of hydrogen sulfide per one hundred (100) cubic feet as determined by quantitative test. 3. Total Sulfur: The gas shall not contain more than 5 grain(s) of total sulfur per one (100) cubic feet of gas as determined by quantitative test. 4. Temperature: The gas shall not have a temperature of less than forty degrees (40o) Fahrenheit or more than one hundred twenty degrees (120o) Fahrenheit. 5. Carbon Dioxide: The gas shall not contain carbon dioxide in excess of two percent (2%) by volume. 6. Oxygen: The gas shall contain no oxygen. 7. Nitrogen: The gas shall not contain nitrogen in excess of two percent (2%) by volume. 8. Non-Hydrocarbons: The gas shall not contain more than four percent (4%) by volume of total non-hydrocarbons. Non-hydrocarbons shall include, but not be limited to, carbon dioxide, nitrogen, sulfur and hydrogen sulfide. 9. Objectionable Liquids and Solids, and Dilution: The gas shall be free of objectionable liquids and solids, shall not contain any hydrocarbons which might condense to free liquids in the pipeline under normal pipeline conditions and shall be commercially free from dust, gums, gum-forming constituents, and other liquids or solid matter which might become separated from the gas in the course of transportation through pipelines. 10. Heating Value: The gas shall not have a gross heating value less than nine hundred fifty (950) Btu per cubic foot of gas or more than one thousand, one hundred fifty (1150) Btu cubic foot of gas. 11. Hydrocarbon Dewpoint: The gas shall not have a hydrocarbon dewpoint greater than forty degrees (40o) Fahrenheit. B. Transporter shall not be obligated to accept gas hereunder, which does not conform to these specifications. In the event gas received hereunder does not conform to these Quality Specifications, Transporter shall notify Shipper of such non-conformance and Shipper shall immediately cease delivery of gas to Transporter or bring such gas within specification. Transporter may elect from time to time to receive such gas not conforming to the Quality Specifications herein. Further, Transporter shall not be obligated to transport any gas which does not meet the Quality Specifications of the party to whom the gas is to be delivered should those specifications be different than the quality specifications herein.
C. Acceptance by either party of gas that does not conform to the quality specifications stated above shall not constitute a waiver of such Quality Specifications by that party in regard to gas received or delivered under the Transportation Service Agreement in the future, nor shall acceptance without an express written waiver constitute a waiver of any claim for damages resulting from delivery of gas not meeting such specifications. SECTION 17 BILLING AND PAYMENT A. For the purpose of billing and accounting for the gas delivered hereunder, the day shall begin at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time and extend to 9:00 a.m. the following day, and the month (hereinafter referred to as "Billing Month"), shall begin at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time on the first day of the calendar month and extend to 9:00 a.m. on the first day of the following calendar month. B. On or before the fifteenth (15th) Business Day of each month, Transporter shall render or cause to be rendered, by mail or facsimile, or other electronic means, to all Shippers an invoice of the amount due for the preceding month setting forth the total quantity of gas delivered by Transporter to Shipper at the Delivery Points and rates for transportation hereunder during such Billing Month. Billings for quantities transported shall be determined on a dry basis. In computing the amounts due, Transporter may utilize estimates of the quantity of gas received from or delivered for the account of Shipper during a month, in place of actual quantities when actual quantities are not reasonably available; provided that adjustments shall be made in later statements for differences between such estimated and actual quantities. When information necessary for billing purposes is in the control of Shipper, Shipper's gas Seller, or Shipper's downstream pipeline or purchaser, Shipper shall furnish such information to Transporter on or before the fifth (5th) day of the calendar month following the month of transportation. C. Within ten (10) days from the date of invoice, Shipper shall pay Transporter the amount due for all gas delivered by Transporter for the account of Shipper at the Delivery Points during the preceding month. Payments to Transporter shall be made by wire transfer to the depository bank in Transporter's invoice, crediting Transporter, such that funds are available to Transporter on or before tenth (10th) day after the date of the invoice. If rendering of an invoice by Transporter is delayed after the fifteenth (15th) day of the month, then the time of payment shall be extended accordingly unless Shipper is responsible for such delay. D. Good Faith Dispute: If a portion of an invoice is disputed, Shipper shall pay when due the portion of the invoice not in dispute and shall at the same time provide Transporter with documentation supporting its dispute. If Shipper, in good faith, disputes the amount of any such bill or part hereof and pays to Transporter such amounts as Shipper concedes to be correct, and furnishes and maintains a good and sufficient surety bond in an amount and with sureties satisfactory to Transporter conditioned upon the payment of any amounts ultimately found due upon such bills after a final determination, then Transporter shall not be entitled to suspend further delivery due to failure to pay such bills. E. Late Payment: In the event Shipper shall fail to pay any amount due Transporter when the same is due, Transporter shall have the option of accruing interest on such unpaid amount at a varying rate per annum (based on a year of 365 or 366 days, as the case may be) which shall be equal to one hundred fifteen percent (115%) of the prime rate charged by JP Morgan Chase Bank, New York, New York, to its largest and most creditworthy commercial borrowers on ninety (90) day commercial loans (but in no event greater than the maximum rate of interest permitted by law) with adjustments in such rate, for any period during which the same shall be overdue, such interest to be paid when the amount past due is paid. Shipper shall not be required to pay interest on any amount billed which is in good faith disputed in writing by Shipper and is ultimately determined to be in error; provided, however, interest shall be due if such amount billed is found not to be in error. If such failure to pay continues for thirty (30) days after payment due date Transporter may suspend deliveries of gas, subject to Transporter providing forty-eight (48) hours written notice, during normal working hours, of such intention to suspend deliveries. In the event Transporter pursues collection on late payment, Shipper shall be liable for all expenses and costs, including court costs and attorney fees, incurred as a result of Transporter's attempts to collect such funds not timely paid. SECTION 18 MEASUREMENT A. The gas delivered to the Receipt and Delivery Points shall be measured with meters constructed and installed, and whose computations of quantity are made, in accordance with the provisions of ANSI-API 2530-AGA-3, or the latest revision thereof as adopted by Transporter. B. The temperature of the gas shall be determined by a recording thermometer so installed that it will record the temperature of the gas flowing through the meters. The average of the record to the nearest one degree (1o) Fahrenheit, obtained while gas is being delivered, shall be the applicable flowing gas temperature for the period under consideration. For all measurement of gas required in this Section, the Btu content per cubic foot shall be determined for a cubic foot of gas at a temperature of sixty degrees (60o) Fahrenheit, at an absolute pressure of 14.73 pounds per square inch on a dry basis. C. The Btu, specific gravity, carbon dioxide, nitrogen and hydrocarbon content of the gas delivered to the Receipt or Delivery Points shall be determined by the use of an on-line chromatograph or by a chromatographic analysis of the gas obtained by a continuous sample or spot sampling method. The results of any sample taken with an on-line chromatograph or continuous sampler shall be applied to the month in which the sample was taken. The results of any spot sample taken shall be applied to the month succeeding the month in which the sample was taken. 1. Delivery Points with consistent quantities of 25 MMcf per day or greater will have an on-line gas chromatograph, subject to adequate site facilities being available, including the availability of electricity and land to accommodate the necessary equipment; otherwise a continuous Btu sampler will be used to determine gas quality. Upon mutual agreement by the parties, an alternate method of Measurement may be used. 2. Receipt Points with consistent quantities of 25 MMcf per day or greater will have an on-line gas chromatograph, subject to adequate site facilities being available, including the availability of electricity and land to accommodate the necessary equipment; otherwise a continuous Btu sampler will be used to determine gas quality. Upon mutual agreement by the parties, an alternate method of Measurement may be used. 3. Receipt Points with quantities equal to or less than 25 MMcf per day will use, at Transporter's option, either a spot sampling technique for single wellhead connections or a continuous sampling technique. D. Adjustment for the effect of supercompressibility shall be made according to the provisions of the latest version of either NX-19 or AGA Committee Report No. 8, as required by Paragraph A. of this Section and as adopted by Transporter, for the average conditions of pressure, flowing temperature, and specific gravity at which the gas was measured during the period under consideration and with the proportionate values each of carbon dioxide, nitrogen and other applicable constituent in the gas delivered included in the computation of the applicable supercompressibility factors. E. If at any time during the term hereof a new method or technique is developed with respect to gas Measurement or the determination of the factors used in such gas Measurement, such new method or technique may be substituted for the gas Measurement set forth in this Section on the date such method or technique is adopted by Transporter. SECTION 19 MEASURING EQUIPMENT AND TESTING A. Installation and Operations: The construction, ownership, operation and maintenance of any measuring facilities necessary to accomplish the receipt of gas by Transporter for the account of Shipper at the Receipt Points and the delivery of gas for the account of Shipper at the Delivery Points shall be the responsibility of Transporter. Each party shall at all reasonable times have access to the premises of the other for inspections, insofar as such premises are connected with any manner of thing covered hereby. The operation of Measuring Equipment, changing of charts and/or collection of information shall be done only by the employees or agents of Transporter at the Receipt and Delivery Points. B. Testing and Repair of Equipment: 1. Transporter and Shipper shall keep their own Measuring Equipment accurate and in repair, making such periodic tests to verify the condition of meter tubes, orifice plate, and chart recorder or flow computer. Such periodic tests shall be performed on a quarterly basis for Receipt Points and a monthly basis for Delivery Points. Both parties agree to give each other or their designee seven (7) calendar days notice prior to such tests of the Measuring Equipment so that, if desired, either party may have its representative present. Either party shall have the right to challenge the accuracy of the other party's equipment, and when challenged, the equipment shall be tested, calibrated and, if required, repaired by the challenged party, the cost of such special test to be borne by the challenged party if the inaccuracy is found to cause the total measured Btu during a month to be more than two percent (2%) of such total measured Btu, but if the inaccuracy is found to cause the total measured Btu during a month to be two percent (2%) or less of such total measured Btu, the cost of such special test shall be borne by the challenging party. If upon any equipment test the inaccuracy and all prior inaccuracies resulting from other equipment tests during the same period are found to cause the total measured Btu during a month to be in excess of two percent (2%) of such total measured Btu and the total measurement adjustment during a month is great than 100 MMBtu, then the registrations thereof shall be corrected for a period extending back to the time such inaccuracy occurred, if such time is ascertainable, and if such time is not ascertainable, then back one-half (1/2) of the time elapsed since the last date of equipment calibration. If upon any equipment test the inaccuracy and all prior inaccuracies resulting from other equipment tests covering the same period are found to cause the total measured Btu during a month to be less than two percent (2%) of such total measured Btu or the total measurement adjustment during the month is less than 100 MMBtu, then the operator of the measuring equipment, at its option, may cause the registrations thereof to be corrected for a period extending back to the time such inaccuracy occurred, if such time is ascertainable, and if such time is not ascertainable, then back one-half (1/2) of the time elapsed since the last date of calibration. Any Measurement Equipment found to be measuring inaccurately in any percentage shall be adjusted at once to read accurately. 2. If, for any reason, the meter(s) are out of service or out of repair so that the amount of gas received and/or delivered cannot be ascertained or computed from the readings thereof, the gas received and/or delivered during the period such meter(s) are out of service or out of repair shall be estimated and agreed upon by the parties hereto by the use of the first applicable of the following methods: a. By comparative utilization of any like check Measurement Equipment installed by Shipper or Shipper's designee if such check Measurement Equipment can be proven and verified to be measuring accurately subject to the check meter provisions in Paragraph E of this Section; or b. By computing the error if the percentage of error is ascertainable by calibration, test or mathematical calculation; or c. By estimating the quantity received and/or delivered by reference to actual receipts and/or deliveries during preceding periods under similar conditions when Transporter's Measurement Equipment was registering accurately. C. Inspection of Charts and Records: The charts and records from the Measurement Equipment shall remain the property of Transporter and shall be kept on file for a period of time not less than two (2) years from the end of the calendar year in which the charts and records were generated or prepared. At any time within such period, upon written request by Shipper, records and/or charts from the Measurement Equipment, together with calculations wherefrom, will be submitted for Shipper's inspection and verification subject to return to Transporter within thirty (30) days from receipt thereof. Shipper or Shipper's designee shall retain its charts and records for the same period of time as Transporter's obligation under this paragraph. Any inquiries regarding Measurement Equipment and Testing, including but not limited to, measurement charts, records, or audits of charts and records shall be directed to Manager, Measurement. D. Telemeter: Transporter and Shipper shall each have the right, but not the obligation, to install and operate telemetering equipment it deems necessary to carry out Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition (SCADA) or other operational needs at any Receipt and/or Delivery Points contemplated hereunder, provided Transporter's normal operations are not impeded.
E. Check Meter: Shipper or Shipper's designee shall have the right to install, maintain as described in Paragraph A. of this Section, and operate such check Measurement Equipment as it may desire, but same shall not interfere with or impede in any way the operation of Transporter's measurement or other equipment hereunder, and all calibrating and adjusting of check meters and changing of charts shall be done by Shipper or its designees. Such check meters may be installed at the Receipt Points only, unless the Delivery Points are at Shipper's or its designee's Pipeline. Further, Transporter must be notified seven (7) calendar days prior to all testing and calibration in order to have a representative present. In the event Transporter proves the inaccuracy of Shipper's check meter or all applicable check meter maintenance records are not available, both parties agree to incorporate the next applicable alternate method detailed in Paragraph B.2. of this Section to resolve the discrepancy. SECTION 20 RECEIPT AND DELIVERY PRESSURES A. All gas delivered hereunder by Shipper shall be delivered at pressures sufficient to enter Transporter's Pipeline System at the working pressures maintained at the Receipt Points from time to time. Transporter shall not be obligated to receive gas hereunder at pressures exceeding the maximum allowable operating pressures of the facilities or pressures prescribed under any applicable governmental regulations. Transporter shall at no time be required, unless otherwise agreed in writing, to construct or modify facilities currently existing, including compression, to effect such receipt, including but not limited to, instances when the upstream facility changes its operating conditions from those in effect at the time the interconnection was completed. B. All gas delivered hereunder by Transporter shall be delivered at pressures sufficient to enter the downstream facilities at the working pressures maintained at the Delivery Points from time to time. Transporter shall not be obligated to deliver gas hereunder at pressures exceeding the maximum allowable operating pressures of the facilities or pressures prescribed under any applicable governmental regulations. Notwithstanding the foregoing, Transporter shall at no time be required, unless otherwise agreed in writing, to construct or modify facilities currently existing, including compression, to affect such delivery including, but not limited to, instances when the downstream facility changes its operating conditions from those in effect at the time the interconnection was completed. C. All gas redelivered at the Redelivery Points shall be redelivered at pressures sufficient to enter the receiving party's facilities at such point; provided, however, Transporter shall not be required to compress gas or be obligated to construct or modify currently existing facilities. SECTION 21 MISCELLANEOUS A. Basic Function: Transporter is first and foremost an intrastate pipeline. Therefore, any Section 311(a)(2) service that Transporter provides will be consistent with and shall not infringe upon its status as a non-jurisdictional intrastate pipeline and shall not subject Transporter to the FERC's Natural Gas Act jurisdiction.
B. Qualified Shippers: In addition to other conditions contained in this Statement of Operating Conditions, transportation services provided by Transporter are available only to Shippers who enter into a mutually acceptable Transportation Service Agreement with Transporter. All transactions on behalf of interstate pipelines or local distribution companies served by interstate pipelines must qualify under the provisions of Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA and the FERC's implementing Rules, Regulations and Orders. If, in the opinion of Transporter, the qualified status of a Shipper or its transaction is in doubt, then such Shipper must apply for and receive a non-appealable, final ruling from the FERC, or any successor agency thereto, affirming the qualifying status of Shipper and its transaction under the provisions of Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA prior to the commencement of transportation services by Transporter. C. Changes to this Statement: Transporter reserves the right to add, delete or modify conditions in this Statement of Operating Conditions at any time in accordance with the FERC's Regulations under 18 CFR Section 284.123(e). A copy of the revised Statement of Operating Conditions will be furnished to Shippers who request it. D. Conflicts and Authority of Statement: The rules and regulations of the jurisdiction agency govern all services provided under Section 311(a)(2), and in the event any contract term or provision is inconsistent with these rules and regulations or this Statement of Operating Conditions, the rules and regulations or this Statement of Operating Conditions will control and the contract will be deemed modified accordingly.
E. Possession and Non-Odorization of Gas: As between Shipper and Transporter, Shipper shall be in exclusive control and possession of the gas deliverable and responsible for any damage or injury caused thereby until the same shall have been received by Transporter for the account of Shipper at the Receipt Points and after delivery of the gas by Transporter for the account of Shipper at the Delivery Points. After delivery of gas by Shipper to Transporter, and until delivery by Transporter to Shipper or Shipper's designee, Transporter shall be in exclusive control and possession thereof and responsible for any injury or damage caused thereby. The Receipt and Delivery Points hereunder shall be deemed to be located at the flanges connecting the facilities owned by Transporter with those facilities owned, leased or used by Shipper or Shipper's designee or its gas supplier for the receipt and delivery of gas hereunder. Each party expressly notifies the other that the gas delivered to the Receipt and Delivery Points hereunder is not odorized. In the event either party, at its own election or pursuant to laws, orders, rules or regulations of any governmental body having jurisdiction, elects or is required to odorize the gas deliverable hereunder, then such party shall give prior written notice to the other of its intention to odorize such gas.
F. Title and Risk of Loss: Shipper warrants for itself, its successors and assigns, that it will have at the time of delivery of Gas at the Receipt Point hereunder either good title or all rights necessary and appropriate to have the Gas transported. Shipper warrants for itself, its successors and assigns, that the Gas it delivers hereunder shall be free and clear of all liens, encumbrances and claims on the title to the Gas; and that it will indemnify and hold harmless Transporter, its officers, agents, employees and contractors from and against any and all suits, claims, liability, loss, damages, costs (including attorney's fees and court costs) or encumbrances whatsoever arising directly or indirectly from and with respect to the title and/or right to Gas tendered to Transporter hereunder. Transporter warrants that at the time of delivery to Shipper at the Delivery Point the Gas delivered hereunder shall be free and clear of all liens, encumbrances and claims on the title to the Gas; and that it will indemnify and hold harmless Shipper, its officers, agents, employees, and contractors against any and all suits, claims, liability, loss, damages, costs (including attorney's fees and court costs) or encumbrances whatsoever arising directly or indirectly from or with respect to the title and/or right to Gas delivered to Shipper as a result of Transporter's possession or transportation hereunder. Title and/or rights to all Gas delivered by Shipper to Transporter for transportation, hereunder will remain with Shipper during transport by Transporter; provided, however, it is understood and agreed that the Gas delivered at the Points of Delivery will not be the identical Gas that was delivered to Transporter for transportation, hereunder, but such Gas will be a part of the commingled delivery of Gas and, for the purpose of Shipper's Transportation Service Agreement, the commingled Gas may be substituted for Shipper's Gas on a heat-equivalent basis. G. Governing Law and Regulations: The interpretation and performance of any Transportation Service Agreement that is subject to this Statement of Operating Conditions shall be governed by, construed, interpreted and enforced in accordance with the substantive laws of the State of Texas, without reference to its choice of law doctrine. Transporter's transportation services are subject to all present and future valid lawful orders of all regulatory authorities now or hereafter having jurisdiction of the services or facilities used to provide such services, including, without limitation, the provisions of Subpart C of Part 284 of the Commission's Regulations. In the event any regulatory body having jurisdiction over the Transportation Service prohibits Transporter from collecting specific rates for the services provided under the Transportation Service Agreement or subjects its transportation facilities to any greater or different regulation or jurisdiction than that existing on the date of initial Transportation Service hereunder (or thereafter as such regulation or jurisdiction may have changed and been accepted), then Transporter shall have the right, upon written notice to Shipper, to terminate the Transportation Service Agreement on the effective date of such regulation, anything herein to the contrary notwithstanding and shall have no liability to Shipper or any other entity in connection with any such termination. H. Arbitration: 1. In the event the Transporter and Shipper are unable to resolve any dispute regarding the application or interpretation of any provision of a Transportation Service Agreement or related transaction, such dispute shall be resolved through mandatory Arbitration under the Rules of the Center for Public Resources Institute for Dispute Resolution, to the extent not inconsistent with the rules specified herein. 2. Within twenty (20) Business Days of either Transporter's or Shipper's written election to the other to arbitrate any disputes which arise under this Agreement, each party shall choose one (1) arbitrator, and within ten (10) Business Days after both such arbitrators are chosen, such arbitrators shall choose a third arbitrator thus completing the whole arbitration panel. Any arbitrator chosen shall be a disinterested party with knowledge of the industry. Any arbitration hereunder shall be conducted in Dallas, Texas. 3. The arbitrator(s), once chosen, shall consider any evidence which the arbitrators deem necessary and shall then accept sealed written resolutions of the subject dispute from each party on a confidential basis to be submitted within twenty (20) Business Days of establishment of the arbitration panel. The written submissions shall be in a form and subject to limitations as may be prescribed by the arbitrators. The arbitrators shall then choose only one of the proposed solutions, (without modification) as the fairest solution to the dispute within ten (10) Business Days of receipt of the written submissions of both parties. In the event of a three-member arbitration panel, a majority vote shall govern. The decision of the arbitrators shall be final and non-appealable. 4. Any expenses incurred in connection with hiring the arbitrators and performing the arbitration shall be shared and paid equally between the parties. Each party shall bear and pay its own expenses incurred in connection with the arbitration, unless otherwise included in a solution chosen by the arbitration panel. In the event either party must file a court action to enforce an arbitration award under this Section, the prevailing party shall be entitled to recover its court costs and reasonable attorney fees. In respect of any suit, action, claim or proceeding relating to this Transportation Service Agreement, each party hereby waives, to the fullest extent permitted by law, any right to jury trial. The existence, contents or results of any arbitration hereunder may not be disclosed without the prior written consent of both parties. The parties submit to the non-exclusive jurisdiction of the courts of the State of Texas. I. LIMITATIONS OF REMEDIES, LIABILITY AND DAMAGES. NO PARTY SHALL BE LIABLE FOR CONSEQUENTIAL, INCIDENTAL, PUNITIVE, EXEMPLARY OR INDIRECT DAMAGES, LOST PROFITS OR OTHER BUSINESS INTERRUPTION DAMAGES, BY STATUTE, IN TORT OR CONTRACT, UNDER ANY INDEMNITY PROVISION OR OTHERWISE. THE LIMITATIONS IMPOSED ON REMEDIES AND THE MEASURE OF DAMAGES IS WITHOUT REGARD TO THE CAUSE OR CAUSES RELATED THERETO, INCLUDING THE NEGLIGENCE OF ANY PARTY, WHETHER SUCH NEGLIGENCE BE SOLE, JOINT OR CONCURRENT, OR ACTIVE OR PASSIVE. J. Assignment: Any transaction entered into that is governed by this Statement of Operating Conditions shall be binding upon and inure to the benefit of the successors, assigns, personal representatives, and heirs of the respective Shipper and Transporter. No assignment of such transaction, in whole or in part, shall be made by Shipper without the prior written consent of Transporter, which consent will not be unreasonably withheld, provided, however, Shipper may transfer its interest to any affiliate by assignment, merger or otherwise without prior written consent of Transporter as long as such entity has a credit status which, in Transporter's opinion, is at least equal to or higher than that of Shipper. K. Effective Date: Unless otherwise provided by the FERC and except as otherwise provided herein, this Statement of Operating Conditions shall become effective the date filed with the FERC.
